-- Lesson: Start Here (35 blocks, 5 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":5,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"If You Need This Right Now"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"If you are in the middle of an argument right now:"},{"type":"text","content":"→ Open the 30-Second Reset. It will help you come back into your body before you say something you cannot take back."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"If the argument just ended and you are still shaking:"},{"type":"text","content":"→ Open the Conflict Recovery Plan. It will help you name what just happened while it is still fresh."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"If your partner just walked out and you do not know what to do:"},{"type":"text","content":"→ Read the opening letter below. You are not alone in this."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"If you are reading this before anything has happened yet:"},{"type":"text","content":"→ Open Part II — The Book. There is no fire."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"Start Here"},{"type":"text","content":"Dear friend,"},{"type":"text","content":"I don''t know exactly what brought you to this kit. Maybe you just had a fight and you are still shaking. Maybe the house is quiet now, too quiet, and you are sitting at the kitchen table with a cup of something cold wondering how it got this bad again. Maybe you have been reading the sales page for a week, going back and forth, trying to decide if this is a thing you are allowed to want."},{"type":"text","content":"Either way, I want you to know that the fact that you are here matters. Really matters."},{"type":"text","content":"I have been working with couples for more than twenty years, and I can tell you something that almost nobody says out loud: the person who opens the kit first is almost always the person who has been carrying more. More of the worry. More of the noticing. More of the quiet decision, over and over, to not give up yet. That is probably you. And I want to honor that before we go any further."},{"type":"text","content":"If you are reading this alone, without your partner knowing, that is completely okay. Some of the most beautiful transformations I have seen started with one person quietly showing up differently. When you stop reacting from the oldest, most scared part of your brain, the entire dynamic starts to shift — even if your partner has not read a single page. You do not need their permission to start. You do not need them to be ready. You just need to be willing to try one thing different than yesterday."},{"type":"text","content":"This kit is designed to meet you where you are right now, not where you think you should be. It is not a textbook. It is not homework. It is not another thing to feel behind on. It is first aid — the tools I give couples when arguments are the primary pain point and the next hard moment is coming whether they are ready or not."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is how to use it: Part I is the Emergency Mini-Kit — five short lessons. If you only ever read those five lessons, the kit has done its job. Every tool in Part I is designed to be used in under five minutes, and most of them work in under thirty seconds. You do not have to understand the whole method to use any of them. You just have to open the one you need."},{"type":"text","content":"Part II is the book. It is longer, and it is meant for a different moment — a quieter one. Saturday morning with coffee. A Tuesday night when the kids are asleep and you finally have forty-five minutes that belong only to you. Part II is where the deeper understanding lives, and it will change the way you hear everything that happens in the next argument. But you do not have to get there today. Today, you just have to open it."},{"type":"text","content":"One more thing, and then I will let you go. This kit is full of words I have written over twenty years, but the real work of your marriage is not in these pages. The real work is in what you choose to do in the next small moment. A softer word. A longer exhale. A hand on your chest when the wave starts to rise. A pause instead of a last word. That is where everything begins to shift."},{"type":"text","content":"You do not have to do it perfectly. You just have to start."},{"type":"text","content":"With love and with hope,"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Trisha"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"How to Use This Kit"},{"type":"text","content":"This kit is designed to be opened twice."},{"type":"text","content":"The first time, you are probably in the middle of something hard. Maybe you just had a fight, or maybe one is coming. The five lessons in Part I: The Emergency Mini-Kit are written for that moment. Everything in Part I is meant to be used in under five minutes. You do not need to read them in order. Start with the Emergency Triage at the top of this lesson and let it point you to what you need."},{"type":"text","content":"The second time, the storm has passed. You have coffee. You have forty-five minutes. You are ready to understand *why* the fight happened the way it did, and what to do differently next time. Part II — The Book — comes next. It is meant to be read in one or two calm sittings, not all at once."},{"type":"text","content":"Both halves use the same tools. The only difference is the depth. If you only ever read Part I, the kit has done its job."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Who this kit is not for"},{"type":"text","content":"This kit is designed for couples where both people are fundamentally safe with each other, even when you are fighting badly. If you are experiencing physical harm, threats, or control in your relationship, this kit is not the right tool for you — what you need is real-time help."},{"type":"text","content":"Please call the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 1-800-799-7233, or text START to 88788. They are free, confidential, and available 24/7. You deserve support and safety."},{"type":"text","content":"If you are in crisis yourself, please call or text 988 (Suicide and Crisis Lifeline). There is no version of you that is not worth reaching out for."},{"type":"divider"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 1
)
AND sort_order = 1;

-- Lesson: The 30-Second Reset (18 blocks, 2 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":2,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"The 30-Second Reset"},{"type":"text","content":"You can do this in the middle of a fight, in the bathroom, in the car, standing in the kitchen pretending to look for something. Your partner does not need to know you are doing it. It takes about thirty seconds."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is what to do:"},{"type":"list","items":["Place one hand over your heart.","Take a slow, steady inhale through your nose until your lungs are nearly full.","Add a small top-off inhale to fill your lungs completely.","Exhale slowly through your mouth with an audible sigh — long and unhurried.","Repeat three times."],"ordered":true},{"type":"text","content":"That is the whole practice."},{"type":"text","content":"You will probably notice softer eyes, a slower heart, shoulders starting to drop, a warmer feeling somewhere in your chest. That is your body coming back online. You have just told your Critter Brain, *\"We''re safe now,\"* and invited your CEO Brain back into the room."},{"type":"text","content":"This is not a magic fix. It will not end the fight. It will not make you feel good about what just happened. What it *will* do is give you about thirty seconds of distance between the moment your nervous system decided the conversation was no longer safe and the words you say next."},{"type":"text","content":"Thirty seconds can change a fight."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"After the Reset"},{"type":"text","content":"You took thirty seconds. Your body is starting to come back online. Now what?"},{"type":"text","content":"If the conversation is still happening and you are going to re-enter it — open the SPARK Method Quick Reference next in this module. Pick one step. Just one. Use it."},{"type":"text","content":"If the conversation is over and you are sitting with the aftermath — open the Conflict Recovery Plan next in this module. It will help you name what just happened while it is still fresh enough to be useful."},{"type":"text","content":"If you are not ready for either and you need to come back to this later — that is okay. Put the kit down. Drink some water. Go to bed if you need to. The kit will still be here tomorrow, and so will the work."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"A quick note afterward"},{"type":"text","content":"If you just used the reset in a real moment, take one more minute now and write down what it felt like. Your body will learn faster if you notice it working."},{"form_id":"post-reset-journal","title":"What did you notice?","fields":[{"id":"what_happened","label":"What was happening right before you did the reset?","type":"textarea","rows":3,"placeholder":""},{"id":"body_after","label":"What did your body feel like afterward?","type":"textarea","rows":3,"placeholder":"Softer shoulders? Slower breath? Still tight but a little less?"},{"id":"what_next","label":"What did you do next?","type":"textarea","rows":3,"placeholder":""}],"type":"fillable_form"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 1
)
AND sort_order = 2;

-- Lesson: The SPARK Method (Quick Reference) (38 blocks, 3 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":3,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"The SPARK Wallet Card"},{"type":"text","content":"*Cut this page out. Fold it in half along the center line for a double-sided card. Keep it in your wallet, your phone case, your nightstand, the kitchen drawer where nobody looks. When you need it, you will not have time to go looking for it.*"},{"type":"text","content":"Important: When you print this page, choose Print at 100% / Actual Size. Do not \"Scale to Fit Page\" — it will shrink the card and the cut marks will not line up."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Card — Front Side"},{"type":"text","content":"``` S    See it happening P    Pause and probe A    Acknowledge what''s real R    Reconnect before you fix K    Kindle what comes next ```"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Card — Back Side"},{"type":"text","content":"``` S    Notice the second your body stops feeling safe."},{"type":"text","content":"P    Breathe. Name what you feel. Do not speak yet."},{"type":"text","content":"A    Validate your partner''s reality before you defend your own."},{"type":"text","content":"R    Say it: \"I''m still here. We''re still us.\""},{"type":"text","content":"K    Come back later to learn, not to litigate. ```"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"SPARK — The Quick Reference"},{"type":"text","content":"The wallet card above is for when you have thirty seconds. This section is for when you have two minutes. The full chapter on SPARK is Chapter 5 — The SPARK Method in Part II, for when you have twenty."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"S — See it happening."},{"type":"text","content":"The moment the conversation shifts from connecting to protecting. You will feel it in your body before you hear it in your words — tight jaw, heat in your chest, the first sentence that comes out sharper than you meant it. Your job is not to stop it. Your job is to *notice* it."},{"type":"text","content":"*Example: \"I noticed my jaw clenched the second she said that.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"P — Pause and probe."},{"type":"text","content":"Stop the momentum. You do not have to say anything yet. Take one breath. Ask yourself, silently: *What am I actually feeling right now?* Not the story about what your partner did — the feeling underneath. Sad. Scared. Alone. Invisible. Name it inside your own head first. That is enough."},{"type":"text","content":"*Example: \"I''m not angry. I''m afraid he''s going to leave me.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"A — Acknowledge what''s real."},{"type":"text","content":"Before you defend your position, validate what is true about theirs. You are not agreeing. You are telling their nervous system it is safe to lower its guard. Validation does not mean agreement — it means recognizing their reality."},{"type":"text","content":"*Example: \"You''re right that I said I would call. I didn''t. That makes sense that you''re upset.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"R — Reconnect before you fix."},{"type":"text","content":"The signal: *I am still here. We are still us.* A hand on theirs. A softer voice. The word \"we.\" The fix comes later — first, the bond. Most couples try to fix before they reconnect, and the fix does not hold."},{"type":"text","content":"*Example: \"I love you. I want to figure this out with you.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"K — Kindle what comes next."},{"type":"text","content":"After the storm, come back to it. Not to re-litigate. To learn. What made it get so hot? What was your Critter Brain trying to protect? What would you want to try differently next time? This is where change lives."},{"type":"text","content":"*Example: \"Can we talk about what happened, from a calm place, tomorrow over coffee?\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*The full SPARK teaching — where it came from, why each step works, and how to practice it — is in Chapter 5 — The SPARK Method in Part II.*"}]}'::jsonb
