-- Lesson: Chapter 1 -- The Moment It Shifts (58 blocks, 7 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":7,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Part II"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Book"},{"type":"text","content":"*The deeper work, for a day when you have time to read.*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"Welcome Back"},{"type":"text","content":"I don''t know how you got to this page."},{"type":"text","content":"Maybe you opened the kit last night when everything was hard, and the tools got you through to morning. Maybe the conversation you were bracing for never actually happened, and here you are with coffee and a quiet hour you did not expect. Maybe you are reading the whole kit in one sitting because that is how you learn. All three are okay. All three are welcome."},{"type":"text","content":"Part II is different from Part I. Part I was designed to be opened in a hurry. Part II is designed to be read slowly, the way you read a book that actually matters to you — in one or two sittings, not a forty-day plan. Forty-five to sixty minutes of reading. A cup of something warm. A comfortable chair. No pressure to take notes, highlight, or \"finish the module.\" If you stop halfway through and come back later, the book will still be here."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is what you should know before we begin."},{"type":"text","content":"This is not a textbook. It is a continuation of the conversation that started in the opening letter of the Emergency Mini-Kit. The voice is the same. The goal is the same. The only thing that changes is the depth."},{"type":"text","content":"You do not need to understand every concept to benefit. I have been teaching couples this material for twenty years, and I can tell you that the couples who get the most out of it are rarely the ones who can define every term. They are the ones who let one idea sink in and change how they notice what happens in their own bodies. If you walk away from this book with one thing — one observation about yourself that you did not have before — this book has done its job."},{"type":"text","content":"This book is for the one who reads it. If you are reading alone and your partner has no idea, that is still going to work. If you are reading with your partner, that is beautiful and rare. Either way, you are the one doing the work right now. That counts."},{"type":"text","content":"And then there is this:"},{"type":"text","content":"The one thing I want you to notice first, above everything else in these chapters, is the moment your body decides the conversation is no longer safe. Everything else in this book is downstream of that moment. If you walk away with nothing but the ability to catch that one moment earlier, a few seconds earlier, you will have done the whole work."},{"type":"text","content":"So that is where we will go first. Chapter 1 is about that moment. It is short. It is the hinge the rest of the book swings on."},{"type":"text","content":"Take your time. Start when you are ready."},{"type":"text","content":"With you,"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Trisha"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 1"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Moment It Shifts"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"[PLACEHOLDER STORY — TRISHA TO REPLACE]"},{"type":"text","content":"There is a couple I worked with once who came into a session with the quietest kind of fight on their faces. She had her coffee in both hands. He had his phone facedown on the table. Neither of them had said anything for about three minutes."},{"type":"text","content":"Finally she said, *\"It was the way you looked at me when I asked about Saturday.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"He blinked. *\"I didn''t look at you any way.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"You did.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"Trisha, she''s making this up.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"I watched her face change. Not a lot. Just a micro-shift, the way a curtain moves in a room where you did not know the window was open. Her eyes went a little flatter. Her shoulders dropped a quarter of an inch. She put her coffee down."},{"type":"text","content":"And in that moment, which took maybe three-quarters of a second, she was gone. Not physically — she was still in the chair. But the person who had been trying to tell him something had just decided it was not worth trying anymore. Her Critter Brain had made the call. The conversation we were supposed to be having was over before either of them said another word."},{"type":"text","content":"He did not see it happen. Neither did she."},{"type":"text","content":"That is what this book is about."},{"type":"text","content":"[END PLACEHOLDER — ~215 words]"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"You know what I am talking about. You have felt it — in yourself, in your partner, probably in both. The tight chest. The sudden heat in your face. The tunnel vision that makes their voice sound a little farther away than it is. The first sentence that comes out before you had any intention of saying it."},{"type":"text","content":"These are not accidents. These are not character flaws. These are the signals your body sends when it has decided — without asking your permission first — that the conversation is no longer safe."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is the thing most couples miss, and here is the reason \"just communicate better\" does not work:"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"The fight does not start when the voices rise. The fight starts about four seconds earlier, in your body, in a place you cannot see."},{"type":"text","content":"By the time the words come out, the decision has already been made. You were not choosing to snap or to shut down or to go cold. Some older, faster part of you made the call, and your mouth caught up with it. You cannot out-communicate a decision your nervous system made four seconds ago — no matter how good you are with words, no matter how much therapy you have had, no matter how much you love the person across the table from you."},{"type":"text","content":"That is not a failure of love. That is how bodies work."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"Everything in this book is downstream of that moment."},{"type":"text","content":"When I tell you about your Critter Brain and your CEO Brain in the next chapter, I am telling you *who* is actually making the decision in that four-second window — and it is not you."},{"type":"text","content":"When I tell you about the 90-Second Wave in Chapter 3, I am telling you *how long* that decision lasts before your body comes back online and you can think again."},{"type":"text","content":"When I tell you about the Zones of Resilience in Chapter 4, I am telling you *where* you live when you are *not* in the middle of one of those moments — and why that turns out to matter far more than what you do during the moment itself."},{"type":"text","content":"When I tell you about the SPARK Method in Chapter 5, I am telling you *what to do* when you notice a shift happening — how to interrupt it, survive it, and come back to each other afterwards, even when you botched the first try."},{"type":"text","content":"But all of it — every framework, every practice, every story — comes back to the same four seconds."},{"type":"text","content":"Your ability to change your marriage starts with your ability to notice that window. That is the whole secret. That is the only thing you need to get right. Everything else is practice."},{"type":"text","content":"Most of the couples I have worked with are not bad at loving each other. They are just working with a nervous system that was built to protect them, and a set of tools that never got introduced."},{"type":"text","content":"You are about to meet those tools."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"So how does your body make a decision that big without asking you first?"},{"type":"text","content":"The short answer is that one part of your brain — a part you inherited from your great-great-great-great grandparents, and theirs — is looking for danger all the time. It is very good at its job. When it decides something is dangerous, it does not pause to discuss. It does not run the decision past you. It just acts."},{"type":"text","content":"The name of that part of your brain is the Critter Brain."},{"type":"text","content":"Let me tell you about it."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*Chapter 2 begins on the next page.*"},{"type":"divider"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 1;

-- Lesson: Chapter 2 -- Your Critter Brain and Your CEO Brain (145 blocks, 16 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":16,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 2"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Your Critter Brain and Your CEO Brain"},{"type":"text","content":"We were just in the moment it shifts. A four-second window in which the person you love became, for a fraction of a second, someone your body had decided was not safe."},{"type":"text","content":"Now let me tell you who is actually running the show in that moment — because it is not you. Not the you who planned to have a calm conversation over coffee. Not the you who loves this person and has loved them for years. Not the you who knows better."},{"type":"text","content":"The you who is running the show in that four-second window is older than all of that. It is a part of your nervous system that was installed before you had language. Its whole job is to keep you alive, and it has exactly one question it is always asking: *Am I safe, or am I in danger?* If the answer is \"danger, even a little,\" it grabs the wheel and drives. No permission. No pause. No consultation with the wiser, more thoughtful parts of you."},{"type":"text","content":"My husband Jeff and I have a nickname for this part of you. We call it the Critter Brain. And the wiser, more thoughtful part — the one that got its keys taken away — we call the CEO Brain."},{"type":"text","content":"These two parts of your brain are not enemies. They are both doing exactly what they were built to do. The problem is that in a hard conversation, one of them is much faster than the other. If you understand how they work together, and how to bring the slower one back online when the faster one has taken over, everything else in this book starts to make sense."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is what you need to know about both of them."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*[The following chapter content is Trisha''s teaching from Module 5.1 & 5.2, lightly edited to remove in-course framing. See `drop-ins/module-5-1-5-2-extracted.md` for the full extraction and `drop-ins/drop-in-diff-report.md` for the edit log.]*"},{"type":"heading","content":"Module 5.1 & 5.2 — Meet Your Nervous System (extracted)"},{"type":"text","content":"*Pause. Breathe. Return to safety together.*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system is one of the most powerful and life-shaping systems in your body — the communication network that determines how you think, feel, and respond in love and in life."},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system shapes every interaction. It decides whether you open up, shut down, or react before you can stop yourself. When you understand it, you gain the power to regulate, repair, and reconnect with yourself and your partner."},{"type":"text","content":"I''ve had the privilege of studying under Leah Davidson, one of the leading voices in nervous-system resilience and trauma recovery. I''ve been in her program for the past two years, learning to integrate this work into relationships and emotional health. The teachings in this chapter are tailored from her framework and layered with my own practiced experience and additional learning over the years."},{"type":"text","content":"By the end of this chapter, you will:"},{"type":"list","items":["Understand the two main \"characters\" running your inner world — your Critter Brain and your CEO Brain","Recognize your body''s automatic reactions — fight, flight, freeze, and fawn","Use both mindset (top-down) and body (bottom-up) tools to calm your system","Expand your Green Zone of safety, where calm, clarity, and connection live","Repair conflict faster by learning how to bring your CEO Brain back online after Critter Brain hijacks the wheel"]},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"01 — The Critter Brain"},{"type":"text","content":"Inside each of us lives a dynamic duo, the two drivers of your emotional life. They''re both brilliant, but they have very different jobs."},{"type":"text","content":"Your Critter Brain is your Survival Driver, and your CEO Brain (prefrontal cortex) is your Growth and Decision Maker."},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Critter Brain — Your Survival Driver"},{"type":"text","content":"Your Critter Brain, sometimes called the dinosaur brain or brainstem, has many nicknames. It''s your in-house security guard: loyal, reactive, and definitely not a fan of taking risks."},{"type":"text","content":"It lives deep in your brainstem and limbic system and runs your automatic survival systems:"},{"type":"list","items":["Heartbeat","Breathing","Reflexes","Digestion","Hormones and Adrenaline"]},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Your Critter Brain:"},{"type":"list","items":["Doesn''t like to take risks or try new things","Avoids growth because it feels unpredictable","Pulls you back to your lowest, most familiar state because it knows you can survive there","Believes safety equals familiarity, even if what''s familiar is miserable","Prefers comfort over courage","Doesn''t plan ahead"]},{"type":"text","content":"It protects. It''s the part of your nervous system that says, \"Nope, too scary, stay small so you can stay comfortable.\""},{"type":"text","content":"That''s why people stay stuck in patterns they hate, not because they''re weak, but because their Critter Brain equates change with danger."},{"type":"text","content":"The Critter Brain is like a smoke alarm. It is quick to react and terrible at distinguishing between burnt toast and a house fire. So when your partner sighs or your child slams a door, your Critter Brain might send the full emergency crew racing to the scene."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s always asking one question: \"Am I safe or am I in danger?\" And if there''s even a chance of pain, panic, or uncertainty, it slams on the brakes."},{"type":"subheading","content":"When the Amygdala Hijacks the Wheel"},{"type":"text","content":"You may have heard the phrase, \"your amygdala is being hijacked.\" That''s exactly what''s happening when your Critter Brain takes control."},{"type":"text","content":"The amygdala is the alarm center deep inside your Critter Brain. Its job is to detect threat, danger, or emotional risk and instantly alert your entire body to respond."},{"type":"text","content":"The moment it senses something unsafe — a sharp tone, a disapproving look, or even a familiar memory — your amygdala hits the panic button before your CEO Brain has a chance to weigh in."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s lightning fast. It bypasses logic. *\"We''re not safe. Do something now!\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"That''s an amygdala hijack, but we''ll keep it simple and call it your Critter Brain. It''s that moment when your body floods with stress hormones, your thoughts narrow, and your words become sharper or quieter. You can''t \"just calm down\" because your Critter Brain has grabbed the wheel and sent your CEO Brain to the backseat."},{"type":"text","content":"The good news is that you can train your body to notice the hijack sooner and recover faster. That''s what this chapter is here to help you do."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Critter Brain in Action — Relationships"},{"type":"text","content":"| Critter Brain''s Move | What it Looks Like | |---|---| | Fight | \"You never listen!\" — sharp tone, high energy, heart pounding | | Flight | \"Forget it.\" — walks away, shuts down, escapes to work or phone | | Freeze | Blank stare, numbness, can''t think or speak | | Fawn | \"It''s fine!\" — appeases, over-apologizes, tries to keep the peace |"},{"type":"text","content":"When your Critter Brain is in charge you can''t think straight, not because you''re broken, but because your body has chosen survival over logic."},{"type":"text","content":"Our work is to notice when the Critter Brain takes the wheel and learn how to calm it so your CEO Brain can drive again."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Individual Reflection"},{"type":"text","content":"*Think of one time your Critter Brain took over this past week.*"},{"type":"list","items":["What did your body do?","What did your mind say?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"subheading","content":"Couple Reflection"},{"type":"text","content":"*Take some time to discuss the following prompts with your partner and create a plan for next time one of you becomes hijacked.*"},{"type":"list","items":["When my Critter Brain is driving, my partner can help by: ___","When my partner''s Critter Brain is driving, I can help by: ___"]},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"02 — The CEO Brain"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The CEO Brain — Your Wise Driver"},{"type":"text","content":"Your CEO Brain lives in your prefrontal cortex, the planner, problem-solver, and compassionate leader. If your Critter Brain''s motto is \"Survive,\" your CEO Brain''s motto is \"Thrive.\""},{"type":"text","content":"It''s the part of you that loves to:"},{"type":"list","items":["Learn new things","Take healthy risks","Dream, plan, and problem-solve","Explore new experiences","See the bigger picture"]},{"type":"text","content":"While your Critter Brain avoids discomfort, your CEO Brain thrives on challenge and change. It loves growth, creativity, and learning from mistakes."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Your CEO Brain:"},{"type":"list","items":["Stays curious instead of critical","Responds with empathy instead of reactivity","Makes decisions that align with your values","Stays open to feedback instead of defensive","Listens with your heart and stays present through hard conversations"]},{"type":"text","content":"But the moment your Critter Brain senses threat, it yanks the wheel away. Your body reroutes blood flow away from your CEO Brain and into survival mode. That''s why, mid-argument, your IQ seems to drop and your CEO has been temporarily \"fired.\""},{"type":"text","content":"The key is not to shame the Critter Brain but to gently recruit your CEO Brain through awareness, curiosity, and safety."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Reflection"},{"type":"text","content":"*Think of one time your CEO brain took the lead this week:*"},{"type":"list","items":["What did you do?","How did that change the tone of your relationship or conversation?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"03 — The Vagus Nerve"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Vagus Nerve — Your Superhighway of Safety"},{"type":"text","content":"Running quietly through your body is a long, wandering nerve called the Vagus Nerve — the word *vagus* actually means \"wanderer.\" And wander it does."},{"type":"text","content":"This nerve connects your brain to your face, heart, lungs, and gut, traveling through nearly every major organ in your torso. It''s the ultimate mind-body messenger — your built-in communication superhighway that keeps every system in sync."},{"type":"text","content":"When it''s working well, you feel safe, connected, calm, and grounded. When it''s disrupted, you may feel anxious, numb, reactive, or shut down."},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Five-Lane Highway"},{"type":"text","content":"Imagine it like a five-lane interstate:"},{"type":"list","items":["Four lanes (80%) send messages from your body up to your brain","One lane (20%) sends messages from your brain down to your body"]},{"type":"text","content":"That means most communication is bottom-up. Your body is constantly whispering to your brain:"},{"type":"list","items":["\"Are we safe?\"","\"Is this familiar?\"","\"Can I rest, or do I need to protect myself?\""]},{"type":"text","content":"This is your body scanning for danger and talking to your brain. This is why you can''t \"think\" your way into calm when your body is signaling danger."},{"type":"text","content":"If you only rely on logic or willpower from the brain, you''re driving against traffic. Driving against traffic means your body and brain are not in sync."},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Language of Safety"},{"type":"text","content":"To truly regulate your nervous system, you have to speak your body''s language: breath, movement, sound, and connection."},{"type":"text","content":"Each time you:"},{"type":"list","items":["Take a slow, intentional breath","Unclench your jaw or shoulders","Make gentle eye contact with someone you trust","Hug, sing, laugh, or even hum softly"]},{"type":"text","content":"...your Vagus Nerve sends a signal to your Critter Brain that says: *\"Stand down, the fire''s out, we''re safe now.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"When that happens, your CEO Brain (the part responsible for clarity, empathy, and decision-making) can finally come back online."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Why this Matters in Relationships"},{"type":"text","content":"Your Vagus Nerve isn''t just about your individual calm; it''s also about co-regulation."},{"type":"text","content":"When your nervous system feels safe, you can help your partner''s system feel safe too. You breathe slower, speak softer, and your tone, face, and presence tell them: *\"It''s okay, you''re safe with me.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"This is one of the greatest gifts you can give each other in healing work — to become a safe harbor for one another''s nervous system."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Power of Practice: Rewiring Your Nervous System"},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system isn''t fixed; it''s trainable. Every breath, every pause, every time you choose safety over reactivity, you are changing the circuitry in your brain."},{"type":"text","content":"Neuroscience calls this neuroplasticity — your brain''s lifelong ability to rewire, rebuild, and relearn new patterns."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s taken your nervous system a lifetime to get where it is today, shaped by your genetics, experiences, stress, and relationships. It''s completely normal that it will take time, repetition, and compassion to change it."},{"type":"text","content":"The beautiful truth is that it can absolutely change."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s not about forcing your nervous system; it''s about inviting it. Each small act of regulation is a quiet vote for healing. These moments can look simple: taking a slow breath before speaking in conflict, relaxing your shoulders when your partner walks in the room, feeling the warmth of a hug, stepping outside for sunlight, or placing a hand on your chest and whispering, \"I''m safe.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Each of these signals safety to your Critter Brain and gently teaches your body that it''s okay to exhale, soften, and trust again."},{"type":"text","content":"When practiced regularly, these small choices begin to add up. Over time, your nervous system learns that safety isn''t just possible, it''s familiar. And when safety becomes familiar, connection begins to flourish."},{"type":"text","content":"With steady practice and patience, you can:"},{"type":"list","items":["Strengthen the pathways of safety and calm","Teach your Critter Brain to stand down faster","Build new wiring for connection, confidence, and resilience"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"Reflection"},{"type":"list","items":["When you feel tense or anxious, what does your body do first — tighten, speed up, or shut down?","What are your body''s signals that it''s moving back toward safety?","Put a hand over your heart and take three slow breaths, then write down what shifted."],"ordered":true},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"04 — The Autonomic Nervous System"},{"type":"text","content":"Your autonomic nervous system runs the behind-the-scenes essentials: your heartbeat, breathing, digestion, and stress response."},{"type":"text","content":"It has two main branches that work together to keep you balanced. Think of them like your car''s gas and brake pedals."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Sympathetic Nervous System (The Gas Pedal)"},{"type":"list","items":["Function: speeds up heart rate, raises alertness, releases adrenaline","Feeling: tense, fast, hot, wired","Role: powers fight/flight"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"Parasympathetic Nervous System (The Brake)"},{"type":"list","items":["Function: slows heart rate, deepens breath, restarts digestion","Feeling: calm, warm, grounded","Role: powers rest, repair, and connection"]},{"type":"text","content":"When your Critter Brain hits the gas (sympathetic), your Vagus Nerve eventually applies the brakes (parasympathetic) to slow things down."},{"type":"text","content":"If you live with your foot on the gas all the time — always rushing, worrying, or multitasking — your braking system weakens. You can start to feel chronically tense or burnt out."},{"type":"text","content":"The goal of this work is to rebuild your braking power. When your body can move smoothly between the gas and brake pedals, you return to calm more easily and stay there longer. That''s what emotional regulation really is. It''s your body''s ability to move through stress and come back home to safety."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"05 — Nervous System 101 (Relationship Edition)"},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system is like a full-time security guard, scanning every moment for cues of safety or danger. It listens through:"},{"type":"list","items":["Outside: sights, sounds, smells, touch, taste","Inside: heartbeat, breath, gut sensations","Between: facial expressions, tone of voice, posture, and energy — especially from your partner"]},{"type":"text","content":"When it senses safety, you connect. When it senses danger, you protect."},{"type":"text","content":"It doesn''t care whether the threat is physical or emotional. It responds the same way. That''s why a raised eyebrow or a sigh can trigger a stress response that feels physical. The tight chest, the pit in your stomach, the shaky hands — it''s your Critter Brain doing its job."},{"type":"text","content":"The good news is, with practice, your body can learn new cues for safety. Over time, you can teach your nervous system that connection can feel safe too."},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Zones of Safety: Hyper, Hypo, and Resilient"},{"type":"text","content":"These are the main states of your nervous system. I like to call them your Zones of Resilience."},{"type":"text","content":"*We''ll explore the full map of these zones in Chapter 4. For now, here''s a quick introduction:*"},{"type":"list","items":["Green Zone — Team Resilient (Safe): Body — relaxed, steady breath. Mind — curious, open, engaged. Relationship — affectionate, calm, playful.","Red Zone — Team Hyper (Fight/Flight): Body — heart racing, tense, hot. Mind — irritable, anxious, scattered. Relationship — reactive, defensive, restless.","Blue Zone — Team Hypo (Shutdown): Body — heavy, numb, flat. Mind — hopeless, disconnected. Relationship — withdrawn, distant, unresponsive."]},{"type":"text","content":"We all move in and out of these zones every single day."},{"type":"text","content":"The goal isn''t to stay in the Green Zone constantly. It''s to notice more quickly when you''ve left it and to know how to find your way back home to safety."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Check-In: \"Where''s My Body Right Now?\""},{"type":"text","content":"*Take a minute to pause and ask yourself:*"},{"type":"list","items":["How''s my breathing?","Where do I feel tension or energy?","Do I want to move or be still?","Which zone am I in — Green, Red, or Blue?"]},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Daily Practice"},{"type":"text","content":"You already met this practice back in Part I — the 30-Second Reset. Here''s the context you didn''t have when you first learned it:"},{"type":"text","content":"The Daily Practice is a simple reset — a bridge back to safety. When done daily, it strengthens the connection between your brain and body so you can return to calm faster and stay there longer. You''ve just told your Critter Brain, \"We''re safe now,\" and invited your CEO Brain back online."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Takeaway Truths"},{"type":"list","items":["Your Critter Brain avoids risk and craves familiarity. It keeps you alive but can also keep you small.","Your CEO Brain thrives on growth, creativity, and new challenges. It leads you toward your potential.","Your Vagus Nerve is your five-lane safety highway, and most communication flows from body to brain.","The sympathetic system hits the gas (fight or flight); the parasympathetic applies the brakes (rest, digest, and connect).","You can''t think your way to calm; you have to feel your way to safety.","Every time you calm your Critter Brain and bring your CEO Brain back online, you expand your capacity for connection, courage, and healing."]},{"type":"text","content":"Your Critter Brain is loyal but fearful. Your CEO Brain is wise and brave. Together, you''ll teach them to drive as a team, one calm, curious mile at a time."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"So: in that four-second window where a conversation turns, your Critter Brain is making decisions at a speed your CEO Brain cannot catch. The Critter Brain is not wrong to do this. It is doing its job. It was built to keep you alive, and it is very good at keeping you alive. The problem is that it cannot always tell the difference between \"this person might hurt me\" and \"this person is my husband of fifteen years who just used a tone I did not like.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Both of those look like danger to the Critter Brain. And both of those get the same treatment."},{"type":"text","content":"This is why \"just communicate better\" is such hollow advice. Communication is a CEO Brain activity. You cannot do it from the Critter Brain. When the Critter Brain has the wheel, the CEO Brain is sitting in the passenger seat reading a magazine, waiting for things to calm down before it offers its opinion."},{"type":"text","content":"So the real question is not: *\"How do I stop the Critter Brain from taking over?\"* You cannot. It is going to take over. That is the whole point of having one."},{"type":"text","content":"The real question is this: How do I bring the CEO Brain back online fast enough to matter?"},{"type":"text","content":"It turns out there is a clear answer to that question, and it is not \"deep breathing.\" It is not \"count to ten.\" It is not \"use I-statements.\" All of those are true enough, but they do not explain the actual mechanism by which a nervous system comes back to calm."},{"type":"text","content":"The actual mechanism is a little wave in your body that lasts about ninety seconds."},{"type":"text","content":"Let me tell you what I mean."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*Chapter 3 begins on the next page.*"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 2;

-- Lesson: Chapter 3 -- Riding the 90-Second Wave (113 blocks, 11 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":11,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 3"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Riding the 90-Second Wave"},{"type":"text","content":"Think about the last time you got hit by a wave of feeling you did not see coming. Not the kind that builds slowly over an afternoon — the kind that lands in one second. A word. A look. A memory. A text with four words in it."},{"type":"text","content":"You probably remember what your body did. Your chest went tight. Your face went hot. Your breath got short in a way you did not notice until someone asked if you were okay. There was a whole minute or so where thinking clearly felt like trying to thread a needle in a car going seventy. And somewhere in the middle of all that, you did or said something you later wished you had not."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is what was actually happening: your nervous system was riding a wave. Not a metaphor. A real, physical wave of biochemical activity that had a beginning, a middle, and, if you did not add fuel to it, an end."},{"type":"text","content":"And the end came faster than most people think."},{"type":"text","content":"The research on this is consistent across nervous-system science: a fully-felt emotional wave — one that you are not suppressing, not performing, not telling yourself a long story about — lasts approximately ninety seconds from rise to fall. Ninety seconds. That is it."},{"type":"text","content":"Everything longer than ninety seconds is not the wave. It is the story you are telling yourself about the wave."},{"type":"text","content":"This is the single most practical piece of neuroscience I have ever taught couples. Because once you know that the wave is ninety seconds, the question changes. It stops being *\"How do I make this feeling go away?\"* and becomes *\"How do I make it through the next ninety seconds without making it worse?\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"Let me show you how."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*[The following chapter content is Trisha''s teaching from Module 5.3, lightly edited to remove in-course framing.]*"},{"type":"heading","content":"Module 5.3 — Mastering the Flow of Emotion (extracted)"},{"type":"callout","icon":"lightbulb","content":"*\"You have to feel it to heal it.\"* — Dr. Edith Eger"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"If we don''t understand what''s moving inside us, the map won''t make sense. The landscape is shaped by the weather, and emotions are the weather. This is where we slow down and learn to work with our emotions instead of fighting against them."},{"type":"text","content":"You''ll see how feelings are energy — how they rise and fall like waves — and how allowing them to move freely builds safety and trust within your nervous system."},{"type":"text","content":"When you allow yourself to simply be with what you feel, without judgment or story, your body begins to soften, your breath steadies, and healing starts."},{"type":"text","content":"By the end of this chapter, you will:"},{"type":"list","items":["Understand how emotions move through the body as waves of energy","Practice the 90-Second Wave technique to regulate in real time","Explore how emotional flow supports nervous-system safety","Identify the stories you attach to emotions and how to release them","Learn how to bring emotional awareness into your relationships through gentle conversation"]},{"type":"text","content":"Every emotion carries a message. When we suppress those messages, they grow louder; when we listen, they soften. This work develops emotional fluency — the ability to recognize, name, and move through what you feel without shame or fear."},{"type":"text","content":"When emotions are allowed to move, your system begins to heal. You reclaim energy, clarity, and compassion that were once locked in suppression or over-reaction."},{"type":"text","content":"And when you can stay connected to yourself in those emotional moments, you create the foundation for deeper connection with others, and a wider Green Zone for life."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"01 — Mastery vs. Control"},{"type":"text","content":"Mastering your emotions has nothing to do with controlling them."},{"type":"text","content":"We''ve all seen what happens when people try to \"be strong\" and shove their feelings down. They look calm on the outside... until one day someone breathes wrong, or the dog knocks over a flower pot, and suddenly there''s a Category 5 emotional hurricane in the kitchen."},{"type":"text","content":"Trying to control your emotions is like shaking a bottle of Coca-Cola and then stuffing Mentos inside before tightening the lid. What happens when you keep that sealed up too long? It EXPLODES!"},{"type":"text","content":"It was never really about the dog or the mess, it''s about everything that''s been quietly stacking up underneath the surface."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Suppressed emotions don''t disappear; they just build pressure."},{"type":"text","content":"When I say \"mastering your emotions,\" I mean understanding your emotional landscape:"},{"type":"list","items":["Knowing the territory and terrain","Where the cliffs and valleys reside","What changes the weather","How to find your way back home to safety"]},{"type":"text","content":"It''s about understanding what''s happening inside you and learning to work with your emotions instead of against them."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"02 — The Palette of Your Emotions"},{"type":"text","content":"Each of us experiences a whole palette of emotions: joy, irritation, anger, delight, longing, tenderness, sadness, love, fear, frustration, awe…"},{"type":"text","content":"Every one of these colors is the way we see and experience the world."},{"type":"text","content":"When you practice gratitude, presence, or compassion, your entire internal atmosphere shifts. Life doesn''t necessarily get easier, but everything feels bigger and brighter."},{"type":"text","content":"On the flip side, when stress, anger, or overwhelm take over, the world suddenly feels smaller, darker, and more personal. The circumstances may be the same, but the lens you''re looking through has changed."},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Power of RAS"},{"type":"text","content":"That shift happens through the Reticular Activating System (RAS) — your brain''s internal filter. It tunes in to whatever you focus on most."},{"type":"text","content":"When you train your attention toward gratitude or peace, your RAS begins noticing more of it. You start seeing what''s good, safe, and stable even in chaos."},{"type":"text","content":"When your focus shifts toward calm and safety, it releases built-up pressure inside. Your nervous system stops bracing for danger and starts exhaling, letting emotional energy move instead of getting trapped."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s never just the situation; it''s your internal landscape — the way you see your world and release the pressure within it."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Reflection"},{"type":"list","items":["What have I been unconsciously training my RAS to focus on — threats or peace?","When I intentionally focus on gratitude, what small differences do I notice in my body or relationships?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"03 — What Emotional Mastery Really Means"},{"type":"text","content":"Emotional mastery means letting yourself feel what you feel without judging or labeling, without attaching stories about what it means. It''s pausing long enough to notice where the emotion lives in your body, what it''s communicating, then letting it move through you."},{"type":"text","content":"Emotions are energy — biochemical waves in the nervous system."},{"type":"text","content":"When fully experienced, each wave lasts about 90 seconds."},{"type":"text","content":"The hours or days of spiraling that follow? Those are powered by the story your mind attaches to the emotion. The emotion is not the problem. The meaning you attach to it is."},{"type":"text","content":"Stories like:"},{"type":"list","items":["\"Something must be wrong\"","\"I shouldn''t feel this way\"","\"I think he''s mad at me\"","\"She''s ignoring me\"","\"They don''t care\"","\"I''m failing\"","\"I must be too much\""]},{"type":"subheading","content":"Reflection"},{"type":"list","items":["Which emotions do I tend to label as \"bad,\" and why?","What story do I tell myself when I feel them?","How might I shift from judgment to curiosity?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Allowing Emotions to Move Through You"},{"type":"text","content":"Mastering your emotions begins by fully experiencing them. This means releasing the judgment, labels, and the ceaseless chatter in your mind."},{"type":"text","content":"It means anchoring yourself in your heart and allowing the emotion to wash over you, roll through you, vibrate through your cells, and then complete its biological cycles. That moment where your nervous system finally signals: *\"I''m safe again.\"*"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Let it Rise. Let it Crest. Let it Fall."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Riding the Wave"},{"type":"text","content":"When you allow emotions to rise and fall like waves with curiosity and compassion, your nervous system learns an important truth. *It''s safe to feel.*"},{"type":"text","content":"When your system feels safe, healing gets easier. Your breath slows, your shoulders loosen, and tension begins to release. The mind quiets, the heart steadies, and the body whispers: *\"We''re okay now.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"You don''t need to cry dramatically, yell, throw things, or explain your emotions like a TED talk. This isn''t about performing or proving anything."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s about permission — quiet, steady permission to simply be human. Your only job is to let the emotion do what it came to do: Move."},{"type":"text","content":"Emotions are waves meant to flow, not get trapped. When you let them move through you, you create space for peace, clarity, and even joy. Not by gripping. Not by numbing. Not by performing. Just by feeling."},{"type":"text","content":"Sometimes that''s sitting quietly with a hand over your heart, sometimes it''s one long exhale, sometimes it''s whispering: *\"Thank you for showing me what I needed to feel.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The 90-Second Wave Practice"},{"type":"text","content":"*Choose one emotion this week and ride the 90-second wave whenever it appears. Record what changes afterward — physically, mentally, emotionally.*"},{"type":"list","items":["Pause — stop fixing or analyzing","Place one hand on your chest or belly","Inhale slowly … exhale slowly","Name what''s here — *\"This is sadness,\" \"This is anger\"*","Notice where you feel it — chest, throat, stomach, pinky toe","Stay with it for 90 seconds","Watch it shift, soften, or move"],"ordered":true},{"type":"text","content":"That''s the wave. That''s mastery in motion."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"A Real-Life Moment"},{"type":"text","content":"Imagine you wake up already tired. You spill orange juice down your white shirt. You step on Legos (which, frankly, should count as a weapon). A text comes in that hits the wrong nerve."},{"type":"text","content":"You feel the heat rising: frustration, overwhelm, irritation."},{"type":"text","content":"Old training says: \"Push it down. Act fine. Keep moving.\""},{"type":"text","content":"New training says: Place a hand on your chest. *\"Pause. Breathe. Let the wave move for 90 seconds.\"* *\"I''m overwhelmed. My body is overloaded.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"No fixing. No drama. No story. Just presence."},{"type":"text","content":"As the Critter Brain relaxes, the CEO Brain returns. Clarity comes back. Breath evens out. Words soften."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Reflection"},{"type":"list","items":["How does my body react when things start to go wrong?","Which part of me (Critter Brain or CEO Brain) usually takes over?","What small cues tell me I''m coming back to center?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"subheading","content":"Another Reflection"},{"type":"list","items":["What emotions do I tend to push down instead of feel?","When I''m overwhelmed, what story does my mind create?","What physical sensations tell me an emotion is rising?","What would it look like to let emotions move through me without judgment?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Partner Discussion"},{"type":"text","content":"*Discuss with your partner what you''ve learned so far using the following as your guide:*"},{"type":"text","content":"Partner A: *\"When I feel ______, my body does ______. In those moments, what I most need is ______.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"Partner B: *\"Thank you for telling me. When that happens, I can try ______.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"*Switch roles. No fixing. No advice. Just seeing each other.*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Invitation"},{"type":"text","content":"Most people spend life either drowning in emotions or running from them. You''re learning a third way — to understand your inner landscape and find your way home."},{"type":"text","content":"Emotions were never meant to be controlled; they were meant to be listened to, honored, and allowed."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Presence > Perfection."},{"type":"text","content":"This work changes everything. Choose one recurring emotion — frustration, sadness, overwhelm, or another. For one week, ride the wave each time it appears."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Bringing it All Together"},{"type":"text","content":"You''ve explored the Critter Brain and CEO Brain, the vagus nerve''s messages of safety and connection, and now the waves of emotion — how they rise, flow, and move through you."},{"type":"text","content":"Before you can chart your emotional landscape, you must understand the weather systems within you — those waves that tell you when you''re safe, activated, disconnected, or ready to return home."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"So now you know: the wave is ninety seconds. If you can get your body through those ninety seconds without adding another drop of fuel — no spiraling story, no escalating words, no rehearsing the next line — the wave passes. Your body comes back online. The CEO Brain walks back into the room and picks up the car keys."},{"type":"text","content":"But there is another piece of this that I need to tell you about before we go any further, because it changes how you hear everything that has come before."},{"type":"text","content":"The wave is ninety seconds. That is true. But who you are when the wave hits depends on where you were living *before* the wave started."},{"type":"text","content":"If you were already tired, already stressed, already holding back a week of small things nobody noticed — the wave hits harder and lasts longer, because your system was already halfway up the hill. If you were resourced, rested, and in your body before the wave hit — you can ride it without it knocking you over."},{"type":"text","content":"This is why couples who \"fight about nothing\" are rarely actually fighting about nothing. They are fighting about the accumulated weight of everything their nervous systems have been carrying since the last time either of them had a full night of sleep."},{"type":"text","content":"And that brings us to the map."},{"type":"text","content":"You already took the Zones of Resilience self-assessment back in Part I. You already have a result. You already know, roughly, which zone you have been living in this week. What you do not yet have is the story of what that result means — the deeper teaching behind it, and what to do with it."},{"type":"text","content":"That is this next chapter."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*Chapter 4 begins on the next page.*"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 3;

-- Lesson: Chapter 4 -- The Zones You Live In (144 blocks, 16 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":16,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 4"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Zones You Live In"},{"type":"text","content":"You already took the assessment back in Part I. You already have a result. Maybe you knew before you started which zone you were going to land in, and the assessment just confirmed what your body had been telling you all week. Maybe the result surprised you. Maybe you are reading this now and suspect you are in a different zone than you were when you marked the boxes."},{"type":"text","content":"All of that is okay. The zones are a map, not a diagnosis. They change. You have probably moved through two or three of them just while making dinner."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is what the assessment cannot tell you, and what this chapter will:"},{"type":"text","content":"The zones are not levels of how well you are doing. They are not a grade. There is no \"better zone\" to aspire to. The Green Zone is your home base, yes — but you are not supposed to live there all the time. Nobody does. Not me. Not my husband Jeff. Not any couple I have worked with in twenty years, no matter how long they have been practicing."},{"type":"text","content":"Your Critter Brain''s whole job is to move you *out* of Green when it senses danger. It is doing that job well. The goal of this chapter is not to make you feel ashamed about leaving Green. The goal is to help you notice when you have left, understand where you went, and know the specific thing your body is asking for to come back."},{"type":"text","content":"Because each zone has a different ask. The thing that gets you back from the Red Zone is completely different from the thing that gets you back from the Blue Zone. Most couples use the wrong tool for the zone they are in, and that is why it feels like nothing works."},{"type":"text","content":"Let me show you the map."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*[The following chapter content is Trisha''s teaching from Module 5.4, lightly edited.]*"},{"type":"heading","content":"Module 5.4 — The Healing Hearts Nervous System Map (extracted)"},{"type":"callout","icon":"lightbulb","content":"*\"Awareness isn''t control — it''s your invitation to return home to yourself.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"Now that you can read your inner weather, it''s time to explore the bigger landscape — your nervous system itself. This chapter is about learning the geography of your system: where emotions live, how they travel, and how to find your way back home when the storm hits."},{"type":"text","content":"By the end of this chapter, you will:"},{"type":"list","items":["Identify your three main nervous-system zones","Recognize the \"caution zones\" on either side of safety","Notice the early warning cues of stress before you lose regulation","Discover your own Map — how you naturally become activated or shut down in real time","Practice returning to calm by using both bottom-up tools and top-down tools"]},{"type":"text","content":"Before you can regulate your nervous system, you have to understand what it''s trying to tell you. And you''ve already begun that work beautifully."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"01 — Critter Brain vs. CEO Brain"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Your Two Brains: Why they Fight for the Wheel"},{"type":"text","content":"By now, you''ve met your Critter Brain and your CEO Brain, and you''ve seen how they sometimes work beautifully together… and other times it feels like two toddlers fighting over the same toy."},{"type":"text","content":"Critter Brain: It''s fast, reactive, and instinctive. It cares about survival. It asks, *\"Am I safe?\"* about 10,000 times a day. Kind of like *\"are we almost there?\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"CEO Brain: It''s your prefrontal cortex. It''s thoughtful, wise, confident, grounded, and relational. It cares about meaning and connection. It asks, *\"What matters here? What''s true?\"*"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Your Nervous System in Motion"},{"type":"text","content":"When life feels steady, the CEO Brain drives while the Critter Brain finally relaxes in the passenger seat, maybe even singing along to the radio."},{"type":"text","content":"But the moment stress hits, even with something small, the Critter Brain bolts upright, grabs the steering wheel with both hands, and shouts, *\"I''ve got this!\"* Not to be difficult, but to protect you."},{"type":"text","content":"Sometimes, it doesn''t take much to stir the waters:"},{"type":"list","items":["A comment.","A look.","A memory that feels a little too familiar."]},{"type":"text","content":"Before your mind even catches up, your body reacts. Your heart quickens, your breath shortens, your muscles brace."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s not a failure — it''s your body doing its job."},{"type":"text","content":"These shifts aren''t meant to be stopped; they''re meant to be understood. The power isn''t in preventing the waves, it''s in learning to feel them, name them, and gently guide yourself back to shore."},{"type":"text","content":"Awareness isn''t control — it''s your first act of regulation and your invitation to return home to yourself."},{"type":"text","content":"And this is exactly why knowing your map matters."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"02 — Window of Tolerance"},{"type":"text","content":"I was first introduced to the concept of the Personalized Menu of Resilience by my mentor, Leah Davidson — one of the leading voices in nervous-system regulation, along with Thais Gibson. Their work opened my eyes to how beautifully we can retrain and orchestrate our nervous systems when we stop fighting against them."},{"type":"text","content":"Over years of study, reflection, and hands-on practice, I''ve woven Leah''s and Thais''s insights with my own coaching work, life experiences, and personal healing to create something unique for the Healing Hearts Program — a Relational Nervous System Map that helps you understand your patterns, your partner''s patterns, and what safety actually feels like in real time. It''s one thing to know the science, it''s another to apply it when you''re tired, activated, and wondering why you just yelled at your beloved dog for shedding."},{"type":"text","content":"Now it''s time to map your landscape — what Dr. Dan Siegel calls your Window of Tolerance."},{"type":"text","content":"I like to think of it as your emotional landscape, the inner terrain your mind and body travel when life feels peaceful, uncertain, or downright overwhelming."},{"type":"text","content":"Every person''s map looks different."},{"type":"list","items":["Some have wide valleys of calm, where stress passes easily and repair feels natural.","Others live near steep cliffs, where one wrong step (or tone of voice) can send things spiraling downward fast, right off the cliff."]},{"type":"text","content":"There''s no \"good\" or \"bad\" map, only awareness. When you understand your landscape, you stop judging your reactions and start guiding them."},{"type":"text","content":"Your job isn''t to avoid leaving your Green Zone — it''s to notice when you''ve wandered away and learn how to find your way back home."},{"type":"text","content":"Remember: This isn''t about perfection or staying Zen 24/7. (If you figure that out, please call me immediately, you can teach and I''ll bring snacks.)"},{"type":"text","content":"It''s about noticing when you''ve left your Green Zone and learning to return with more ease and less shame. The more you practice, the stronger your safety grows — within yourself and within your relationship."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"03 — Your Emotional Landscape Map"},{"type":"text","content":"Hold your hands out in front of you, one 6 inches above the other."},{"type":"text","content":"This space between your hands represents your Green Zone, your home base of calm and safety. It sits right in the middle, between the highs of stress and the lows of shutdown — the balanced center where you feel grounded, steady, and connected."},{"type":"list","items":["Above it lies the Hyper Zones — where your system revs up and energy rises.","Below it is the Hypo Zones — where everything begins to slow or even shut down completely for protection."]},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Five Zones"},{"type":"text","content":"As we move through this together, remember: your Green Zone sits right in the middle. It''s your steady center, your home base of safety, connection, and resilience."},{"type":"text","content":"But for now, we''ll start at the top, where activation is in full force, and then work our way down."},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system is always shifting along this map, and learning to recognize where you are on it is the beginning of every healing choice you make."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Red Zone — Team Hyper"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"Your body hits the gas to survive.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"When stress keeps coming and your system doesn''t feel safe, your Critter Brain jumps into overdrive."},{"type":"text","content":"Adrenaline floods your system, and your CEO Brain goes offline because logic and love don''t matter when your body thinks it''s in danger. Your body prepares for protection, not connection."},{"type":"text","content":"You''re not choosing to lose control — you''re just trying to stay alive."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Example"},{"type":"text","content":"This is the moment you storm out or slam the door. It''s not you being dramatic (well… maybe a little bit). It''s your Critter Brain yelling, *\"I''m not safe!\"* even though your partner is just trying to talk to you."},{"type":"text","content":"Now, without judgment, notice:"},{"type":"list","items":["What is my Critter Brain trying to tell me? Maybe it''s shouting, *\"I''m scared,\"* or *\"I just need to be heard.\"*","Where do I feel that charge in my body? What happens to my breathing, posture, or tone?","What story does my mind start telling me?"],"ordered":true},{"type":"text","content":"As you do, gently remind yourself, *\"I''m activated, and my body is signaling for support. I know how to find my way back.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"That''s your bottom-up approach in action. That''s where regulation truly begins — not by fighting the Red Zone, but by getting curious about what it''s trying to protect. From there, you can start creating the care it''s asking for."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Resetting the Red Zone (Full Activation / Fight-Flight)"},{"type":"text","content":"Grab some ice and hold it in your hands, or place a cool cloth on the back of your neck. This simple act grounds you in the present moment, helping your body shift out of stress and back into safety and rest."},{"type":"text","content":"You can also take a slow, steady inhale through your nose, filling your lungs about three-quarters full. Hold for one count, then fill them the rest of the way and pause for a count of four at the top of your breath. Exhale through your mouth, a little slower than your inhale — four breaths just like that — activating your Vagus Nerve through a bottom-up approach."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Yellow Hyper Zone — Going into Team Hyper"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"You can feel your system starting to rev up.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"This is that subtle moment before full activation — when something small suddenly starts to feel big."},{"type":"text","content":"Maybe it''s a tone, a look, a text that feels a little off, or the sting of being ignored. You''re not in full fight-or-flight yet, but your Critter Brain has perked up and your CEO Brain just dimmed the lights a little."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s like your foot''s on the brake, but with each breath, you''re pressing harder on the gas. The engine''s heating up fast — and at this point, you can go either way: ease off the gas and settle your system, or keep pressing and feel it start to spiral out of control."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Example"},{"type":"text","content":"Your partner walks in late, heads straight to the fridge, and doesn''t even say hello. That quick spark you feel — the one that flares up after waiting all day to connect — turns into *\"Are you kidding me right now?\"* energy bubbling up inside."},{"type":"text","content":"That''s your Yellow Zone speaking: *\"Warning — system warming up!\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"The goal isn''t to bury it, but to catch it before it escalates and you say something you''ll later regret."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Resetting the Yellow Zone (Early Activation)"},{"type":"list","items":["Unclench your jaw.","Drop your shoulders.","Exhale twice as long as you inhale.","Then anchor into your five senses — notice 5 things you can see, 4 things you can touch, 3 things you can hear, 2 things you can smell, and 1 thing you can taste.","Maybe it''s the hum of the fridge or the sunlight on the counter — subtle signals that tell your body, *\"I''m safe right now.\"*","Whisper, *\"This is energy, I''m ok.\"*"]},{"type":"text","content":"As you do this, you''re engaging your Vagus Nerve — the body''s built-in braking system that helps you return to calm."},{"type":"text","content":"That''s your first turn of the wheel back toward regulation, before the Critter Brain takes over completely."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Green Zone — Team Resilient"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"This is where safety, clarity, and connection live.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"Your body is steady and grounded; your mind is clear; your heart is open. This is your optimal state. You are calm yet alert, peaceful yet engaged."},{"type":"text","content":"Your CEO Brain is back at the wheel, calm and in control. Meanwhile, your Critter Brain can finally kick back in the back seat, take a nap, and stop singing off-key to the radio while trying to grab the wheel."},{"type":"subheading","content":"What Green Zone Communication Sounds Like"},{"type":"list","items":["*\"Hey, I know things got a little heated earlier... can we take a breath and try again?\"*","*\"I really appreciate how you handled that; I felt seen.\"*","*\"I can tell you''re having a rough day. Do you want space or a hug?\"*","*\"That came out wrong. What I meant was, I love you and I want to understand.\"*","*\"Let''s press pause and go for a walk. We''ll figure this out together.\"*","*\"Thank you for showing up with me.\"*","*\"I feel calm and connected...\"*"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"Finding Your Green Zone (Home Base & Regulation)"},{"type":"text","content":"Take a slow breath in through your nose and let it out gently. Now, close your eyes for a few seconds and ask yourself:"},{"type":"list","items":["What does my Green Zone feel like in my body?","Where do I feel warmth or ease?","What helps me know I''m safe, calm, and connected?"]},{"type":"text","content":"Now picture your partner:"},{"type":"list","items":["What does their Green Zone look like to me?","How do I know when they''re in it? (Their voice softens? They reach for my hand? They smile?)"]},{"type":"text","content":"Take one more deep breath and anchor this image in your mind. This is your home base — the place you''ll always be learning to return to, together."},{"type":"text","content":"When both partners are in Green, connection feels natural and repair happens faster. This is home base — the space where you both remember, *\"We''re on the same team.\"*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Yellow Hypo Zone — Going into Team Hypo"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"When your system quietly whispers, ''I''ve had enough,'' a deep sense of fatigue begins to set in.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"After too much stress or stimulation, your nervous system begins pressing the brakes. You''re not fully shut down yet, but you''re definitely slowing — like your internal battery is flashing low power mode."},{"type":"text","content":"You might:"},{"type":"list","items":["Sigh more often.","Zone out mid-conversation.","Scroll your phone instead of replying.","Say, *\"I''m fine,\"* when you''re clearly not.","Stare at the wall, start to feel numb and like you just don''t really care."]},{"type":"text","content":"It''s that space where you''re still functioning, but everything feels heavier — like you''re moving through molasses. You crave quiet but don''t know how to ask for it. Even small interactions feel like too much."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Example"},{"type":"text","content":"Your partner starts sharing something emotional, and you catch yourself nodding, but your brain is quietly buffering. You care deeply, but you simply don''t have the bandwidth."},{"type":"text","content":"That''s your Yellow Hypo Zone speaking, gently saying, *\"Please don''t ask me to run one more errand, solve one more problem, or feel one more feeling.\"*"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Resetting the Yellow Hypo Zone (Power-Down / Withdrawal)"},{"type":"text","content":"You''re feeling disconnected because you''re depleted — learning to refuel before your system fully powers down."},{"type":"list","items":["Step outside for a few breaths of sunlight.","Take a sip of water.","Stretch or play a favorite song.","Do one small thing that reminds your body, *\"I''m still here.\"*"]},{"type":"text","content":"Remind yourself that you''re alive: light movement, hydration, sunlight, music, conversation."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Blue Zone — Team Hypo"},{"type":"text","content":"*\"When everything inside you just… stops.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"This is the place beyond exhaustion. Beyond overwhelmed. Where your system finally says, *\"I''m done.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"It''s not sadness exactly — it''s the absence of feeling. You''re not running, not fighting, not even thinking. You''re just… numb."},{"type":"text","content":"Your Critter Brain has hit the emergency brake and pulled you into hibernation. It''s not a choice — it''s protection."},{"type":"text","content":"Everything slows. Time blurs. You go through the motions, but nothing really lands. Your body feels very heavy, your mind foggy, and your heart far away."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Example"},{"type":"text","content":"Your partner asks, *\"Are you okay?\"* and you can barely find words. You stare at the wall, scroll without seeing, or sit in silence because even answering feels impossible."},{"type":"text","content":"That''s your Blue Zone saying, *\"I can''t do this right now. I just need to disappear for a bit.\"*"},{"type":"subheading","content":"What it Feels Like"},{"type":"list","items":["Disconnected from yourself and everyone else","No motivation, no spark, no care","Thoughts thick like mud","Shame for \"checking out\""]},{"type":"text","content":"But you''re not broken — you''re offline."},{"type":"subheading","content":"Resetting the Blue Zone (Full Shutdown / Freeze)"},{"type":"text","content":"This isn''t laziness or failure — it''s biology."},{"type":"text","content":"Your nervous system starts to shut down to protect you from overwhelm, emotional overload, and exhaustion. The way out isn''t by pushing harder; it''s through safety, softness, and small sparks of life gently returning."},{"type":"text","content":"It''s time to wake up the nervous system:"},{"type":"list","items":["Start with warmth — a blanket, sunlight, warm drink, or holding your own hand.","Listen to music with emotion.","Sip water or take one slow walk to the mailbox — tiny movements wake the system.","Let someone sit beside you without fixing you.","Whisper softly, *\"I''m still here. I just need time to come back.\"*"]},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Overview of the Emotional Landscape"},{"type":"text","content":"| Zone | State | Driver | Feels Like | Shift Strategy | |---|---|---|---|---| | Red (Hyper) | Full Activation / Fight-Flight | Critter Brain driving | Anger, panic, urgency, racing thoughts | Step away, move or shake your body, cold water/ice, deep breathing, gentle self-talk | | Yellow Hyper | Early Activation / Mild Dysregulation | Critter Brain alert, CEO brain dimming | Irritated, tense, restless, annoyed, shorter fuse, sarcasm | Name it out loud, long exhales, unclenching jaw, 5 senses | | Green | Home Base / Regulation / Team Resilient | CEO Brain driving | Connection, humor, empathy, playfulness | Maintain routines, rest, gratitude, laughter, connection, mindful movement | | Yellow Hypo | Early Shutdown / Fatigue / Withdrawal | Critter Brain alert, CEO brain dimming | Foggy, tired, disengaged, disinterested | Light movement, hydration, sunlight, gentle connection, music, gratitude check-in | | Blue (Hypo) | Full Shutdown | Critter Brain driving | Numb, heavy, disconnected, checked out | Gentle warmth, safe presence, movement, soft conversation, celebrate tiny wins |"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"So that is the map."},{"type":"text","content":"Five zones, each one temporarily accurate, each one adaptive in its own way, each one asking for a different kind of care. Red asks for discharge — ice, movement, long exhales. Yellow Hyper asks for interruption — naming it, unclenching the jaw, anchoring in the senses. Green asks for maintenance — routines, rest, gratitude. Yellow Hypo asks for gentle re-entry — sunlight, hydration, a little music. Blue asks for warmth and presence — a blanket, safe company, a whispered *\"I''m still here.\"*"},{"type":"text","content":"Knowing your zones tells you *where* you are. It gives you information. It gives you a map. It tells you what your body is asking for, instead of what you think you should be doing."},{"type":"text","content":"But information is not enough. You also need a *method* — a thing you can actually do when your Critter Brain has taken over and the 90-second wave has started and you are not in your Green Zone. Something concrete. Something you can practice. Something you can teach your muscle memory to reach for when thinking clearly is not available."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"That is what SPARK is."},{"type":"text","content":"You have been meeting it in pieces since Part I — the wallet card, the quick reference, the letters — but you have not yet seen the whole method, and you have not yet been told the story of how each step fits with everything you just learned about your nervous system."},{"type":"text","content":"Chapter 5 is where that happens. It is the longest chapter in the book, and it is the chapter I have been building the whole rest of this toward. This is the one that changes how the next fight ends."},{"type":"text","content":"Take a breath. Turn the page."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*Chapter 5 begins on the next page.*"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 4;

-- Lesson: Chapter 5 -- The SPARK Method (87 blocks, 8 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":8,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 5"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The SPARK Method"},{"type":"text","content":"Three chapters ago, we talked about the four-second window."},{"type":"text","content":"Two chapters ago, we talked about who is actually running the show during those four seconds — and why logic and love do not matter to the part of your brain that is making the decision."},{"type":"text","content":"One chapter ago, we talked about the ninety-second wave your body rides once the Critter Brain takes the wheel. And then we talked about the map — the zones you are living in between the waves, and how where you live when the wave hits shapes how hard it knocks you over."},{"type":"text","content":"Everything in those chapters was the build-up."},{"type":"text","content":"This is the method."},{"type":"text","content":"SPARK is not five separate tricks. It is one sequence — one choreography — that interrupts the Critter Brain, rides the wave without adding fuel, and brings you back to your Green Zone in the only order that actually works. Most couples who try to repair a fight go in the wrong order, and that is why their repairs do not hold. They try to *reconnect* before they have *acknowledged*. They try to *acknowledge* before they have *paused*. They try to *pause* before they have even *seen* that something shifted. The repair collapses because the foundation was not there yet."},{"type":"text","content":"SPARK is the order."},{"type":"text","content":"I have been teaching it to couples for twenty years. Jeff and I use it in our own marriage — badly sometimes, beautifully sometimes, but always eventually. I am not going to tell you we have perfected it. I am going to tell you it works, even when you do not."},{"type":"text","content":"Here is everything I know about how to use it."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*[The following chapter content is Trisha''s full SPARK teaching from Module 1.4, including the SPARK Pact worksheet and the Individual and Couple Reflection prompts.]*"},{"type":"heading","content":"Module 1.4 — Pause & Repair (extracted)"},{"type":"text","content":"*Conflict isn''t your breaking point — it''s your breakthrough.*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"A Fight that Could Change Everything"},{"type":"text","content":"It''s an ordinary evening. A small disagreement — perhaps over plans or a forgotten chore — spirals quickly. Voices rise. Your heart races. You''re either snapping back with sharp words or retreating into silence. It''s a moment every couple recognizes."},{"type":"text","content":"But here''s the hope: this fight doesn''t have to end in distance. It can mark the start of something stronger — if you choose to pause and repair."},{"type":"text","content":"When conflict flares up, your brain senses danger. The amygdala, often called the \"critter brain,\" kicks in and shifts you into survival mode. In that moment, logic fades as your prefrontal cortex, the part of your brain responsible for reasoning and decision-making, or your \"CEO,\" steps back. Whenever this happens, empathy fades and reactivity surges."},{"type":"text","content":"In high-conflict marriages, unresolved arguments can deepen emotional distance, breed resentment, and erode hope. Every harsh exchange or silent standoff risks pulling you apart — unless you step in with the right tools."},{"type":"text","content":"Every couple faces conflict; it''s part of sharing a life. What matters is what follows. Pause & Repair, enriched with the SPARK Method, equips you to transform tension into growth."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"The Pause & Repair Blueprint"},{"type":"subheading","content":"01 — Recognize Hijacking"},{"type":"text","content":"The first step is to recognize when your \"critter brain\" hijacks the conversation."},{"type":"text","content":"How to spot it: Raised voice, sudden silence, racing heart, shallow breath, the strong urge to \"win\" or be \"right.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Quick Cue: Ask yourself, \"Am I trying to protect or connect right now?\""},{"type":"text","content":"Scale it: On a scale of 1 (calm) to 10 (hijacked), agree on a pause point in each conflict — like 6 — and honor it."},{"type":"subheading","content":"02 — Pause with Purpose"},{"type":"text","content":"Pausing isn''t avoidance; it''s a courageous choice to prioritize your relationship over the urge to defend or control. Remember to communicate with your partner when you''re needing a pause, do not simply stonewall, give the silent treatment, or just walk away."},{"type":"text","content":"Start Your Pause: Use your cue for a time-out. Try a hand signal, or stating \"I need 20 minutes\" to your partner."},{"type":"text","content":"Regulate Your Nervous System: Step away and reset."},{"type":"list","items":["Breathe — Breathe in for 4 seconds, hold for 4, then breathe out for 4.","Move — Walk outside, stretch, go for a quick jog, or shake your body to release tension.","Cool Off — Splash your face with cold water, have a cold shower, try an ice plunge, or hold ice cubes in your hands.","Reflect — Write down your feelings, ask yourself, \"What''s really beneath this?\""]},{"type":"text","content":"Partner Tip: Set a time (15–60 min) and keep it. Trust begins here."},{"type":"subheading","content":"03 — Reset with Intention"},{"type":"text","content":"You''re back — not to argue, but to rebuild. Soften your approach and invite connection."},{"type":"text","content":"Re-Enter Gently: \"Can we try again?\" or \"Are you ready to talk?\""},{"type":"text","content":"Own Your Part: \"I raised my voice because I felt overwhelmed — I want to do better\" or \"I shut down when I should''ve stayed present.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Set the Stage: Open the door to connection. \"I''m here to hear you.\""},{"type":"subheading","content":"04 — Repair with SPARK"},{"type":"text","content":"S — See P — Pause A — Acknowledge R — Reconnect K — Kindle"},{"type":"text","content":"The SPARK Method guides you to repair with depth and heart, closing the emotional gap step by step."},{"type":"text","content":"See: Look at them, listen fully with your heart — no interrupting. Let them share their truth, raw and real. Nod or offer a gentle look to show you''re present."},{"type":"text","content":"Pause & Probe: Take a breath, then ask with care: \"What felt hardest about that?\" or \"What did you need in that moment?\" Be curious to understand, not judge."},{"type":"text","content":"Acknowledge & Validate: Reflect their feelings. \"I see that upset you — it makes sense\" or \"I get how my reaction hurt you.\" Honor their experience without fixing or fighting it. Validation doesn''t mean agreement, it means recognizing their reality."},{"type":"text","content":"Reconnect: Offer repairs, such as an apology or ask what they need, and then reaffirm — \"I''m in this with you.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Kindle: End with warmth — a long hug, holding hands, a shared breath, an inside joke. Ask \"what helps us feel close again?\""},{"type":"callout","icon":"lightbulb","content":"*\"Compromise isn''t surrender — it''s crafting a path forward together. The strongest couples don''t bury the pain; they face it with courage and heal it with grace.\"* — Trisha Jamison"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Your SPARK Pact"},{"type":"text","content":"*Fill this out together, keep it where you''ll see it — like on your fridge or in your phone.*"},{"type":"text","content":"Our Pause Number: on a scale of 1 (calm) to 10 (hijacked) — *e.g. 6*"},{"type":"text","content":"My Reset Move: _______________________________________"},{"type":"text","content":"Your Partner''s Reset Move: _______________________________________"},{"type":"text","content":"Our SPARK Ritual: *e.g. breathing, walking, journaling*"},{"type":"text","content":"Our Pause Cue: *a time-out hand signal/phrase*"},{"type":"text","content":"*What does SPARK look like for you?*"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Individual Reflection"},{"type":"text","content":"*These prompts are your space to reflect, uncover, and grow. Your answers are saved — come back to them anytime. When you are done, consider sharing them with your partner during a calm moment using the Couple Reflection below.*"},{"form_id":"spark-individual-reflection","title":"The Five Reflection Prompts","intro":"These are the five themed reflections I have been giving couples for twenty years. Take your time. There are no right answers. Your words are private and will be saved so you can come back and build on them.\n","fields":[{"id":"spotting_my_hijack","label":"1. Spotting My Hijack — What does my Critter Brain feel like when conflict starts? What is the number where I know I need to pause?","type":"textarea","rows":5,"placeholder":"Racing heart? Tight chest? Hot face? What happens first?"},{"id":"my_pause_power","label":"2. My Pause Power — What helps me calm myself during a pause, and how safe do I feel calling for one?","type":"textarea","rows":5,"placeholder":"Deep breathing, walk, cold water, something else?"},{"id":"uncovering_the_beneath","label":"3. Uncovering the Beneath — In our last conflict, what was I really feeling under my reaction? What did I need but could not say?","type":"textarea","rows":5,"placeholder":"Look underneath the surface reaction."},{"id":"repair_that_resonates","label":"4. Repair That Resonates — What would meaningful repair look like for me? What words or actions would hit home?","type":"textarea","rows":5,"placeholder":"A certain phrase? A touch? Time to talk?"},{"id":"my_growth_edge","label":"5. My Growth Edge — What is one thing I do in conflict (snap, shut down, defend)? How could pausing or SPARK help me change it?","type":"textarea","rows":5,"placeholder":"Name it with compassion. You are not the pattern — you can see it."}],"instructions":"You do not have to answer all five in one sitting. Start with the one that catches your eye. If you get stuck, leave it blank and come back. Your answers are saved — every time you save, the new version replaces the old one, so edit freely.","type":"fillable_form"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Couple Reflection"},{"type":"text","content":"*To be discussed together, or written separately and shared in a safe conversation.*"},{"type":"subheading","content":"1. Our Conflict Dance"},{"type":"list","items":["What does escalation look like in our relationship? Are there early signs we can spot to pause sooner?","What''s our usual conflict pattern (trigger → reaction → disconnect)?","Where in that cycle can we pause or repair to change the outcome?"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"2. Building a Safe Pause"},{"type":"list","items":["How do we each feel about calling for a pause?","What''s one pause cue (word, gesture) we can agree on that feels natural for both of us?"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"3. Regulation as a Team"},{"type":"list","items":["What helps each of us regulate after a fight? (e.g. breathing, moving) How can we support each other''s reset?"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"4. Crafting Our SPARK"},{"type":"list","items":["What would it feel like if we truly saw each other in a fight — really listened, no interruptions?","How can we acknowledge and validate each other better? What words or actions make us feel truly heard?"]},{"type":"subheading","content":"5. Our Vision for Repair"},{"type":"list","items":["What does meaningful repair look like for us as a couple — a hug, a promise, a quiet moment?"]},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"So there it is. The whole method."},{"type":"text","content":"You have the five steps. You have the Pact you can fill out with your partner. You have the reflection prompts I have watched hundreds of couples work through. You have the wallet card and quick reference from Part I for when thirty seconds is all you have. You have the full teaching you just read. If you only ever use one of these things, use the wallet card — it is the minimum dose that still works."},{"type":"text","content":"But I need to tell you something honest before we go any further."},{"type":"text","content":"Knowing SPARK and *using* SPARK are not the same thing. The first three times you try it in a real fight, you will probably forget at least one step. Maybe two. Maybe you will remember all five and use them in the wrong order. Maybe you will nail it the first time and then completely forget it exists for the next fight. All of this is normal. The method gets stronger with repetition, and repetition means you have to try it, fail partway through, and try it again."},{"type":"text","content":"That is the whole practice."},{"type":"text","content":"And here is the part most couples do not expect: the most important work does not happen during the fight. It happens after."},{"type":"text","content":"What you do in the hour after an argument ends — the reflection, the naming, the quiet noticing — is where actual change lives. Not the heroic in-the-moment SPARK repair. The quiet follow-up that nobody sees. That is the part that, over time, rewires the pattern."},{"type":"text","content":"Chapter 6 is about that quiet follow-up. It is the shortest chapter in the book. It is also the one most people skip."},{"type":"text","content":"Please do not skip it."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*Chapter 6 begins on the next page.*"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 5;

-- Lesson: Chapter 6 -- After the Storm: Your Practice Plan (22 blocks, 3 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":3,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Chapter 6 — After the Storm: Your Practice Plan"},{"type":"text","content":"Here is the truth about every method I have ever taught couples: the method itself is not the work. The *practice* is the work. The couples who change their fights are not the ones who memorized SPARK the fastest. They are the ones who kept using the tools in small, unimpressive moments — the dishes, the laundry, the Sunday afternoon when nothing is wrong — so that when a hard moment came, their muscle memory was ready."},{"type":"text","content":"That is what this chapter is about."},{"type":"text","content":"I am going to give you a seven-day practice plan. It is small on purpose. It is designed to be invisible to your partner if you are doing it alone, and low-stakes enough that you cannot fail at it. Each day has one task. Each task takes less than five minutes. Most of them take less than thirty seconds."},{"type":"text","content":"Do not try to do all seven days at once. Do not try to do them perfectly. Do not worry if you skip a day and pick it back up. The goal of the plan is not to finish. The goal is to start a muscle."},{"type":"text","content":"If you get to day seven and you still have not used SPARK in a real argument, that is okay. The practice itself is changing you, even when it feels like nothing is happening."},{"plan_id":"7-day-spark-practice","title":"The 7-Day SPARK Practice","intro":"Check off each day as you complete it. Add a short note about what you noticed — it does not have to be profound. Even \"nothing happened today\" is information.\n","days":[{"day":1,"title":"Just notice","body":"You are not trying to change anything today. Today, all you have to do is notice when your Critter Brain takes over. You do not need to stop it. You do not need to react differently. Just notice — \"That was my Critter Brain\" — and write down, at the end of the day, what your body was doing in the moment (tight jaw, hot face, a decision made in the car). That is the whole assignment.\n","prompt":"What did your body do today when something activated you?","prompt_rows":3},{"day":2,"title":"Your Pause Number","body":"Pick a number, one to ten, that means \"I need to pause.\" Mine is six. Share it with your partner in a calm moment — not in a fight. Say something like, \"I read this thing and I want to try something. My Pause Number is six. If I ever say it, it means I need twenty minutes.\" That is it for today. You do not have to use it yet.\n","prompt":"What number did you pick, and how did the conversation with your partner go (even if it was just \"okay\")?","prompt_rows":3},{"day":3,"title":"The 30-Second Reset","body":"Use the reset from Part I once today. Not in a fight — in an ordinary moment. While you are making coffee. Before a meeting. Sitting in the car before you go into the store. Just do the sequence. Hand on heart, three slow breaths, audible sigh on the exhale. Notice how your body is different after.\n","prompt":"When did you do the reset, and what did you notice?","prompt_rows":3},{"day":4,"title":"One SPARK step, low stakes","body":"Pick the SPARK step that feels easiest for you. Use it once today, in a small moment where nothing is actually on the line. Maybe you use See and notice when a small irritation starts to rise. Maybe you use Acknowledge and validate something tiny your partner said. Maybe you use Reconnect with a hand on their shoulder when you are both in the kitchen. One step. One moment. That is enough.\n","prompt":"Which step did you try, and what happened?","prompt_rows":3},{"day":5,"title":"Reflect","body":"Take ten quiet minutes today. Not with your partner — by yourself. Look back at the last four days and answer two questions — What did I notice? Where did my Critter Brain show up? If nothing comes up, that is fine too — that is information.\n","prompt":"What did you notice, and where did your Critter Brain show up?","prompt_rows":4},{"day":6,"title":"Try a full sequence","body":"If you can. If a real moment comes up today, try the whole SPARK sequence, even if you do it imperfectly. S, P, A, R, K, in order. You will probably forget at least one step. That is how it is supposed to go. Notice where it got hard.\n","prompt":"Which step was hardest? Which came most naturally?","prompt_rows":3},{"day":7,"title":"Recovery Plan","body":"Fill out the Conflict Recovery Plan from Part I, either about the fight from Day 6 or about an older fight you never processed. Do it alone. You are writing it for you, not for your partner. When you are done, notice what came up — and decide whether any of it is something you want to share when you are both in your Green Zone.\n","prompt":"What came up for you while filling it out?","prompt_rows":4}],"closing":"You have completed the seven days. If it felt like nothing happened, remember — the practice is changing you, even when you cannot see it. Come back to this page whenever you want to run the practice again. The tools are already in your body now.","type":"practice_plan"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"subheading","content":"When you get stuck"},{"type":"text","content":"Here are the places couples usually stall. If you recognize yourself in any of these, you are not failing. You are right on track."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"\"I tried SPARK and my partner did not notice I was doing anything differently.\""},{"type":"text","content":"That is okay. The first three or four times, they are not supposed to notice. SPARK works whether or not your partner knows it is happening. Your job is not to get credit. Your job is to interrupt the pattern. The credit, if it comes, comes later."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"\"I did the 30-Second Reset and it did not calm me down.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Do it again. And again. And again. Your body needs repetition. The reset is not a magic spell — it is a message to your Critter Brain, and the Critter Brain does not always trust the first message. Keep sending it."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"\"We are back in the same fight pattern we had a year ago.\""},{"type":"text","content":"That is the pattern showing you what needs more work. Patterns do not get better by force. They get better by being noticed, over and over, until the noticing itself changes what comes next. The fact that you are in the same fight and you can see it is the fight is already new."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"\"My partner is not reading this kit and probably will not.\""},{"type":"text","content":"You do not need them to. This is the whole point of the Start Here letter in Part I. One person quietly showing up differently changes the whole dynamic, even if the other person does not know what changed. You are enough to start this."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"\"I tried all of this and something is still wrong.\""},{"type":"text","content":"Come find us. healingheartscourse.com. You are not alone, and this kit is not the end of what is available. Jeff and I built a whole program for the couples who have done the first aid and are ready to do the deeper work. If that is where you are, we are here."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"text","content":"*You have everything you need.*"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 2
)
AND sort_order = 6;

-- Lesson: Afterword (13 blocks, 2 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":2,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"Afterword"},{"type":"text","content":"You did this."},{"type":"text","content":"You opened a kit that probably felt like one more thing you did not have time for, and you actually read it. You went into the parts that hurt. You looked at the moment your nervous system decides a conversation is no longer safe, and you looked at what your own Critter Brain tends to say in that moment, and you probably saw yourself in places that did not feel good. That is hard. That matters. That is not a small thing."},{"type":"text","content":"Most people think the work of healing a relationship is the big gestures — the apology, the grand talk, the week away, the promise. I have been doing this for twenty years, and I can tell you it is not. The work is the small, unseen moments nobody else notices. The longer exhale. The softer word. The hand that reaches across the table a little earlier than you would have reached yesterday. The decision to stay in the room for one more minute when your Critter Brain is telling you to leave."},{"type":"text","content":"Those are the moments this whole book was written to help you notice."},{"type":"text","content":"If you are doing this work alone, without your partner knowing, that is honorable. That is real. It counts just as much as anything you could do together. Maybe more, because you are doing it without the validation of someone noticing you are different. There is nobody clapping for you. And you are still showing up."},{"type":"text","content":"One day, weeks from now, something small will happen. Your partner will say something that would have sent you straight into the Red Zone six months ago, and you will feel the wave start to rise, and you will place a hand on your chest, and you will take one long exhale, and you will say something you never would have been able to say before. It will not feel like a victory. It will feel almost invisible — so small you might miss that it happened."},{"type":"text","content":"But you will know. And you will know that this is where everything starts to shift."},{"type":"text","content":"You did not break your relationship in a day. You will not fix it in one either. But you can change the very next fight."},{"type":"text","content":"Go do it."},{"type":"text","content":"With so much hope for what is ahead,"},{"type":"bold_text","content":"Trisha"},{"type":"divider"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 3
)
AND sort_order = 1;

-- Lesson: About Trisha and Jeff (21 blocks, 3 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":3,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"About Trisha and Jeff"},{"type":"text","content":"[TRISHA — PLEASE REPLACE THIS ENTIRE SECTION WITH YOUR OWN BIO AND ORIGIN STORY. Target: ~500 words across 2 pages. The placeholder below is a structural sketch only and is not in your voice — it should not ship.]"},{"type":"text","content":"[PLACEHOLDER START]"},{"type":"text","content":"Trisha Jamison has been working with couples for over twenty years. She teaches a blend of nervous-system science, attachment work, and practical conflict-repair frameworks she developed through years of coaching couples, studying under teachers like Leah Davidson and Thais Gibson, and living through her own marriage."},{"type":"text","content":"Her husband, Dr. Jeff Jamison (MD, FAAFP), is a board-certified family physician who brings the medical and nervous system perspective to their work together. He also contributed the clinical framing for much of the neuroscience in this book, including the Critter Brain and CEO Brain teaching and the polyvagal applications."},{"type":"text","content":"They live in Utah with their family, and they are the founders of Healing Hearts Consulting, LLC — the company behind this book, the full Healing Hearts Program, the Spark Challenge, and the broader community of couples they have been walking with for decades."},{"type":"text","content":"[Photo of Trisha + Jeff]"},{"type":"text","content":"The story of why we made this. [Trisha: one paragraph here about the moment you knew you had to write this program — the specific couple, the specific realization, the specific thing that was missing from the way relationship work was usually taught. Keep it personal. Keep it honest.]"},{"type":"text","content":"How we work. [Trisha: one short paragraph about the philosophy — faith-informed but not preachy, nervous-system-grounded, story-led, written for couples who are tired of advice that does not work in the moment.]"},{"type":"text","content":"Come find us. If something in this kit landed for you — or if something did not — we want to hear from you. Jeff and I read everything. The website has a contact form, or you can email hello@healingheartscourse.com. If you are in a dark place, please reach out to the crisis resources in the Resources section below first. But if you just want to tell us what the kit meant to you, or ask a question, or let us know you are still out there trying — we are here."},{"type":"text","content":"[PLACEHOLDER END]"},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"Resources"},{"type":"subheading","content":"Come find us"},{"type":"text","content":"| Resource | Where | |---|---| | The main website | healingheartscourse.com | | The full program (Healing Hearts) | healingheartscourse.com/programs | | The Spark Challenge *(free 7-day email course)* | healingheartscourse.com/spark |"},{"type":"subheading","content":"A book I recommend"},{"type":"text","content":"*Hold Me Tight* by Dr. Sue Johnson. She is the founder of Emotionally Focused Therapy, and her book is the clearest explanation I have read of why attachment injuries repeat — and what it takes to interrupt them. If the SPARK Method in Chapter 5 landed for you, *Hold Me Tight* is a natural next read. It will expand your vocabulary for everything we just talked about."},{"type":"text","content":"I do not get paid to recommend it. I just think it is good."},{"type":"subheading","content":"If you need help right now"},{"type":"text","content":"If you are in crisis: Please call or text 988 (Suicide and Crisis Lifeline) in the United States. Free, confidential, 24/7."},{"type":"text","content":"If you are experiencing domestic violence: This book is not a substitute for professional help. Please contact the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 1-800-799-7233, or text START to 88788. You deserve support and safety."}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 3
)
AND sort_order = 2;

-- Lesson: What Comes Next (21 blocks, 3 min)
UPDATE lessons
SET content_json = '{"estimated_minutes":3,"blocks":[{"type":"heading","content":"What Comes Next"},{"type":"text","content":"If the Conflict Rescue Kit is first aid, the full Healing Hearts Program is rehabilitation."},{"type":"text","content":"The kit you just read is a piece of the program — a carefully selected piece, the one you needed most if conflict is the primary pain point. But it is a piece. The full program is eight modules and thirty-two lessons that go far beyond conflict: attachment styles, the patterns we inherited from our childhoods, the core wounds that shape who we reach for when we are hurting, the stories we tell ourselves when we feel alone, the legacy we are building together."},{"type":"text","content":"Jeff and I designed it for couples who have done the first aid and are ready to do the deeper work."},{"type":"text","content":"It is not for everyone. It is for couples who want to go slowly and thoroughly, who are willing to sit with hard questions for more than one afternoon, and who believe their relationship is worth the investment of real time and real attention. That means it is not an impulse buy. It is a decision."},{"type":"text","content":"If that sounds like you — or if you want to know more — here is where to find it."},{"type":"bold_text","content":"healingheartscourse.com/programs"},{"type":"text","content":"One more thing. The program is the deeper work, yes. But the work you did in this kit was also real work. If you used the tools in these pages in one real conversation, and it went even a little differently than it would have gone before, you have already done something that matters. You did not need the bigger program to do that. You needed this. You needed a moment. And you made it happen."},{"type":"text","content":"Everything else is what comes after."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"heading","content":"Acknowledgments"},{"type":"text","content":"[TRISHA — PLEASE REPLACE THIS ENTIRE SECTION. Target: ~250 words, 1 page. Your list of people to thank. The placeholder below is a structural sketch only.]"},{"type":"text","content":"[PLACEHOLDER START]"},{"type":"text","content":"Thank you first to the couples who have trusted me with their stories over the last twenty years. You are the teachers. I am the scribe. Without you, nothing in this book would exist. Your courage, your patience with yourselves and with each other, your willingness to show up in hard rooms and try one more thing — all of it lives in these pages."},{"type":"text","content":"Thank you to Jeff, for [Trisha: fill in — how many years of marriage, and what it has meant]. You are the reason I know the nervous-system science in this book actually works in real life, because we have practiced it together in our own worst moments and found our way back. Every story in this book that is not about someone else is about us."},{"type":"text","content":"Thank you to Leah Davidson and Thais Gibson for the foundational nervous-system work that so much of Chapter 2 through Chapter 4 is built on. You opened my eyes to how beautifully we can retrain our own nervous systems when we stop fighting them."},{"type":"text","content":"Thank you to [Trisha: team members — Desirae, Makayla, Chase? Others? Add the names that matter.]."},{"type":"text","content":"Thank you to every person who has ever listened to a session, read a draft, or asked a question that made me think harder."},{"type":"text","content":"And thank you, reader, for opening this."},{"type":"text","content":"— Trisha"},{"type":"text","content":"[PLACEHOLDER END]"}]}'::jsonb
WHERE module_id = (
  SELECT m.id FROM modules m
  JOIN courses c ON c.id = m.course_id
  WHERE c.slug = 'rescue-kit'
    AND m.sort_order = 3
)
